          "body": "Judah's address to Joseph in 44:18-34 is the longest single speech in the book of Genesis, and its length is itself an argument. It moves through five layers: historical recapitulation (what was asked and answered about the family, 44:19-23), the return to Jacob and his grief (44:24-29), the present crisis and its consequences for Jacob's life (44:30-31), the binding obligation of surety (44:32), and the climactic offer (44:33-34). The speech is a masterwork of ancient rhetoric — it piles pathos upon pathos (the aged father, the dead brother, the bound souls, the oath sworn) until the emotional and moral logic is irresistible. What is most striking is what is absent: there is no self-justification, no blame-shifting toward Benjamin, no attempt to negotiate a lesser penalty. Judah does not say 'I am innocent' — he says 'take me instead.' Derek Kidner (Genesis, TOTC) notes that Judah's speech is the moral culmination of the Joseph narrative and the moment that makes Joseph's revelation possible in the next chapter."
